thaway|page=38|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Uhelszki|first=Jaan|date=September 2002|title=Rock Implosion|journal=Alternative Press|issue=170|pages=18\u201319|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Winwood|first=Ian|date=February 18, 2012|title=10 Years of Life on Mars|journal=Kerrang!|publisher=Bauer Media Group|issue=1402|pages=20\u201323|ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Discogs master|176307|30 Seconds to Mars|type=album}}\n\n{{Thirty Seconds to Mars}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:30 Seconds To Mars (Album)}}\n[[Category:2002 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Thirty Seconds to Mars albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Bob Ezrin]]\n[[Category:Concept albums]]\n[[Category:Immortal Records albums]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records albums]]\n", "name_user": "2606:a000:112a:c7b4:2dc3:79b0:5511:8b42", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/30_Seconds_to_Mars_(album)"}
{"title_page": "Exposition internationale du bicentenaire de Port-au-Prince", "text_new": "{{Infobox World's Fair\n| box_width       = \n| class           = Universal\n| category        = 2\n| image           = Dumarsais estime portrait.jpg\n| image_width     = \n| caption         = Dumarsais Estim\u00e9\n| year            = 1949\n| name            = L'Exposition Internationale de port au Prince 1949\n| motto           = 200 years Port au Prince\n| building        = \n| area            = {{convert|30|ha|acre|abbr=off}}\n| invent          = \n| visitors        =  \n| organized       = Dumarsais Estim\u00e9\n| cnt             = \n| org             = \n| biz             = \n| country         = [[Haiti]]\n| city            = [[Port-au-Prince]]\n| venue           = [[Gulf of Gon\u00e2ve|Gonave Bay]]\n| coord           = \n| cand            = {{start date|1948|10|12}}\n| award           = {{start date|1948|12|05}}\n| open            = {{start date|1949|12|01}}\n| close           = {{start date|1950|06|08}}\n| prevexpo        = [[1939 New York World's Fair]]\n| prevcity        = [[New York City]]\n| nextexpo        = [[Expo 58]]\n| nextcity        = [[Brussels]]\n| suppl           = Specialised Expositions\n| prevsuppl       = [[International Exhibition on Urbanism and Housing (1947)]]\n| prevsupcity     = [[Paris]]\n| nextsuppl       = [[The International Textile Exhibition]]\n| nextsupcity     = [[Lille]]\n| simuni          = \n| simspe          = [[Universal Sport Exhibition (1949)]] in [[Stockholm]] and [[The International Exhibition of Rural Habitat]] in [[Lyon]]\n| simhor          = \n| simoth          = \n| website         = \n}}\nThe '''Exposition internationale du bicentenaire de Port-au-Prince''' was a world's fair held in [[Port-au-Prince]], [[Haiti]] in [[1949]] to mark 200 years since Port-au-Prince's foundation.\n\n==Formations==\nPresident [[Dumarsais Estim\u00e9]] argued in 1948 for an exposition to demonstrate Haitian culture to other countries and encourage tourism and committed $1 million (then almost three-quarters of Haiti's annual budget) to the project.<ref name=\"FindPelp314\">{{cite encyclopedia\n | title = Port-au-Prince 1949-1940\n | author = Kimberly D. Perle\n | encyclopedia = Encyclopedia of World's Fairs and Expositions\n | page=314\n | editor-last = Pelle\n | editor-first = Findling\n | publisher = McFarland & Company, Inc\n | year = 2008\n | id =\n | isbn = 978-0-7864-3416-9\n | accessdate = }}</ref>\n\nThe fair opened on ground at the [[Gulf of Gon\u00e2ve|Gonave Bay]] which had been cleared of houses and landscaped with gardens, parks and tall coconut and palm trees<ref name=\"FindPelp314\" />\n\n==Opening==\nThere were two opening ceremonies: the first on December 8, 1949 and the second on February 12, 1950.<ref name=\"FindPelp315\">{{cite encyclopedia\n | title = Port-au-Prince 1949-1940\n | author = Kimberly D. Perle\n | encyclopedia = Encyclopedia of World's Fairs and Expositions\n | page=315\n | editor-last = Pelle\n | editor-first = Findling\n | publisher = McFarland & Company, Inc\n | year = 2008\n | id =\n | isbn = 978-0-7864-3416-9\n | accessdate = }}</ref>\n\nDuring the first ceremony, a telegram from US president [[Harry S. Truman]] to Haitian president [[Dumarsais Estim\u00e9]] was read out, a parade of US soldiers and marines and a US Air Force squadron flew overhead, and the national exhibits and amusement area opened.\n\nDuring the second ceremony, the international as well as the official pavilions were opened. Displays were on show from [[Argentina]], [[Cuba]], [[France]], [[Guatemala]], [[Italy]], [[Mexico]] and [[Venezuela]],<ref name=\"FindPelp315\" /> with [[Vatican City]] providing a chapel.\n\n==Art and music==\nAn art competition was held, with [[Gesner Abelard]] winning a bronze prize, and [[Jacques-Enguerrand Gourgue]] a gold.<ref name=\"JEG\">{{cite web|url=http://www.egallery.com/artists/?id=119|accessdate=23 July 2012|title=Jacques-Enguerrand Gourgue &#124; The Electric Gallery - Egallery - Fine Art - The Art Shopping Source}}</ref>\n\n[[Marian Anderson]], \n[[Carlos Beltr\u00e1n (musician)|Alberto Beltran]], \n[[Frantz Casseus]], \n[[Celia Cruz]], \n[[Miles Davis]], \nIssa El Saeih, \n[[Dizzy Gillespie]],\nErnst Lamy, \n[[Ti Ro Ro]], \n[[La Scala]] singers, \nmembers of the Grand National Opera New York,  \n[[Daniel Santos (singer)|Daniel Santos]],<ref name=\"lotsofpeople\">{{cite web|url=http://pikliz.fotki.com/discover_europe/discover-haiti/haiti-dantan-corrige/port-au-prince-lesc-51.html|language=French|accessdate=23 July 2012|title=Photo: F\u00eate du Bicentenaire - 8 D\u00e9cembre 1949. &#124; Il \u00e9tait une fois Haiti...(1\u00e8re partie). album &#124; Pikliz.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322113634/http://pikliz.fotki.com/discover_europe/discover-haiti/haiti-dantan-corrige/port-au-prince-lesc-51.html|archive-date=22 March 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n[[Don Shirley]]<ref name=\"donshirleytribute\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nathankramer.com/donshirley/bio.htm|accessdate=23 June 2012|title=Don Shirley - biography}}</ref>\nand [[Bebo Valdes]]<ref name=\"lotsofpeople\" /> \nall performed during the exposition.\n\n<!-- this has the number of paid attendees\n<ref name=\"FindPelp430\">{{cite encyclopedia\n | title = Appendix E:Fairs That Never Were\n | encyclopedia = Encyclopedia of World's Fairs and Expositions\n | page=430\n | editor-last = Pelle\n | editor-first = Findling\n | publisher = McFarland & Company, Inc\n | year = 2008\n | id =\n | isbn = 978-0-7864-3416-9\n | accessdate = }}</ref>-->\n== Legacy==\n     Following the close of the exposition many of the pavilions were used for Haitian Governmental Buildings.  The Pavilion of Haiti was converted into the Legislative Assembly Building.  The Post Pavilion became a Post Office.  The Guatemala Pavilion became the home of the Haiti Red Cross, and the Vatican Pavilion became a church.  The devastating earthquake of 2010 laid waste to many buildings in Haiti including most of these exposition buildings including the Legislative Building, Red Cross, and Post Office.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/1949-port-au-prince Official website of the BIE]\n* [http://islandluminous.fiu.edu/part09-slide18.html The International Exposition of Port-au-Prince 1949-50], by Hadassah St. Hubert. Retrieved 10 March 2013\n* {{cite book | language = French | title = Exposition internationale 1949-1950 - bi-centenaire de Port-au-Prince 1749-1949 (oficial catalog of the exhibition, printed in 200 copies) | page= | editor-last = | editor-first = | publisher = | year = 1949 | id = | isbn = | url = http://ufdc.ufl.edu/AA00010663/00001/4j | accessdate = 2014-03-10}}\n\n{{coord|18.5494|N|72.3484|W|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:1949 festivals]]\n[[Category:1949 in Haiti]]\n[[Category:20th century in Port-au-Prince]]\n[[Category:Port-au-Prince]]\n[[Category:World's fairs in North America|Haiti]]\n\n{{List of world exhibitions}}\n{{Haiti-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox World's Fair\n| box_width       = \n| class           = Universal\n| category        = 2\n| image           = Dumarsais estime portrait.jpg\n| image_width     = \n| caption         = Dumarsais Estim\u00e9\n| year            = 1949\n| name            = L'Exposition Internationale de port au Prince 1949\n| motto           = 200 years Port au Prince\n| building        = \n| area            = {{convert|30|ha|acre|abbr=off}}\n| invent          = \n| visitors        =  \n| organized       = Dumarsais Estim\u00e9\n| cnt             = \n| org             = \n| biz             = \n| country         = [[Haiti]]\n| city            = [[Port-au-Prince]]\n| venue           = [[Gulf of Gon\u00e2ve|Gonave Bay]]\n| coord           = \n| cand            = {{start date|1948|10|12}}\n| award           = {{start date|1948|12|05}}\n| open            = {{start date|1949|12|01}}\n| close           = {{start date|1950|06|08}}\n| prevexpo        = [[1939 New York World's Fair]]\n| prevcity        = [[New York City]]\n| nextexpo        = [[Expo 58]]\n| nextcity        = [[Brussels]]\n| suppl           = Specialised Expositions\n| prevsuppl       = [[International Exhibition on Urbanism and Housing (1947)]]\n| prevsupcity     = [[Paris]]\n| nextsuppl       = [[The International Textile Exhibition]]\n| nextsupcity     = [[Lille]]\n| simuni          = \n| simspe          = [[Universal Sport Exhibition (1949)]] in [[Stockholm]] and [[The International Exhibition of Rural Habitat]] in [[Lyon]]\n| simhor          = \n| simoth          = \n| website         = \n}}\nThe '''Exposition internationale du bicentenaire de Port-au-Prince''' was a world's fair held in [[Port-au-Prince]], [[Haiti]] in [[1949]] to mark 200 years since Port-au-Prince's foundation.\n\n==Formations==\nPresident [[Dumarsais Estim\u00e9]] argued in 1948 for an exposition to demonstrate Haitian culture to other countries and encourage tourism and committed $1 million (then almost three-quarters of Haiti's annual budget) to the project.<ref name=\"FindPelp314\">{{cite encyclopedia\n | title = Port-au-Prince 1949-1940\n | author = Kimberly D. Perle\n | encyclopedia = Encyclopedia of World's Fairs and Expositions\n | page=314\n | editor-last = Pelle\n | editor-first = Findling\n | publisher = McFarland & Company, Inc\n | year = 2008\n | id =\n | isbn = 978-0-7864-3416-9\n | accessdate = }}</ref>\n\nThe fair opened on ground at the [[Gulf of Gon\u00e2ve|Gonave Bay]] which had been cleared of houses and landscaped with gardens, parks and tall coconut and palm trees<ref name=\"FindPelp314\" />\n\n==Opening==\nThere were two opening ceremonies: the first on December 8, 1949 and the second on February 12, 1950.<ref name=\"FindPelp315\">{{cite encyclopedia\n | title = Port-au-Prince 1949-1940\n | author = Kimberly D. Perle\n | encyclopedia = Encyclopedia of World's Fairs and Expositions\n | page=315\n | editor-last = Pelle\n | editor-first = Findling\n | publisher = McFarland & Company, Inc\n | year = 2008\n | id =\n | isbn = 978-0-7864-3416-9\n | accessdate = }}</ref>\n\nDuring the first ceremony, a telegram from US president [[Harry S. Truman]] to Haitian president [[Dumarsais Estim\u00e9]] was read out, a parade of US soldiers and marines and a US Air Force squadron flew overhead, and the national exhibits and amusement area opened.\n\nDuring the second ceremony, the international as well as the official pavilions were opened. Displays were on show from [[Argentina]], [[Cuba]], [[France]], [[Guatemala]], [[Italy]], [[Mexico]] and [[Venezuela]],<ref name=\"FindPelp315\" /> with [[Vatican City]] providing a chapel.\n\n==Art and music==\nAn art competition was held, with [[Gesner Abelard]] winning a bronze prize, and [[Jacques-Enguerrand Gourgue]] a gold.<ref name=\"JEG\">{{cite web|url=http://www.egallery.com/artists/?id=119|accessdate=23 July 2012|title=Jacques-Enguerrand Gourgue &#124; The Electric Gallery - Egallery - Fine Art - The Art Shopping Source}}</ref>\n\n[[Marian Anderson]], \n[[Carlos Beltr\u00e1n (musician)|Alberto Beltran]], \n[[Frantz Casseus]], \n[[Celia Cruz]], \n[[Miles Davis]], \nIssa El Saeih, \n[[Dizzy Gillespie]],\nErnst Lamy, \n[[Ti Ro Ro]], \n[[La Scala]] singers, \nmembers of the Grand National Opera New York,  \n[[Daniel Santos (singer)|Daniel Santos]],<ref name=\"lotsofpeople\">{{cite web|url=http://pikliz.fotki.com/discover_europe/discover-haiti/haiti-dantan-corrige/port-au-prince-lesc-51.html|language=French|accessdate=23 July 2012|title=Photo: F\u00eate du Bicentenaire - 8 D\u00e9cembre 1949. &#124; Il \u00e9tait une fois Haiti...(1\u00e8re partie). album &#124; Pikliz.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322113634/http://pikliz.fotki.com/discover_europe/discover-haiti/haiti-dantan-corrige/port-au-prince-lesc-51.html|archive-date=22 March 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n[[Don Shirley]]<ref name=\"donshirleytribute\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nathankramer.com/donshirley/bio.htm|accessdate=23 June 2012|title=Don Shirley - biography}}</ref>\nand [[Bebo Valdes]]<ref name=\"lotsofpeople\" /> \nall performed during the exposition.\n\n<!-- this has the number of paid attendees\n<ref name=\"FindPelp430\">{{cite encyclopedia\n | title = Appendix E:Fairs That Never Were\n | encyclopedia = Encyclopedia of World's Fairs and Expositions\n | page=430\n | editor-last = Pelle\n | editor-first = Findling\n | publisher = McFarland & Company, Inc\n | year = 2008\n | id =\n | isbn = 978-0-7864-3416-9\n | accessdate = }}</ref>-->\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/1949-port-au-prince Official website of the BIE]\n* [http://islandluminous.fiu.edu/part09-slide18.html The International Exposition of Port-au-Prince 1949-50], by Hadassah St. Hubert. Retrieved 10 March 2013\n* {{cite book | language = French | title = Exposition internationale 1949-1950 - bi-centenaire de Port-au-Prince 1749-1949 (oficial catalog of the exhibition, printed in 200 copies) | page= | editor-last = | editor-first = | publisher = | year = 1949 | id = | isbn = | url = http://ufdc.ufl.edu/AA00010663/00001/4j | accessdate = 2014-03-10}}\n\n{{coord|18.5494|N|72.3484|W|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:1949 festivals]]\n[[Category:1949 in Haiti]]\n[[Category:20th century in Port-au-Prince]]\n[[Category:Port-au-Prince]]\n[[Category:World's fairs in North America|Haiti]]\n\n{{List of world exhibitions}}\n{{Haiti-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Mikeinlv", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exposition_internationale_du_bicentenaire_de_Port-au-Prince"}
